name: fibre production, jute, retting | stalk | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/20812/documentation

In practice, jute retting activity involves immersion of the bundles of jute into stagnant water in the jute cultivation field, tanks, ponds, ditches etc., or in slowly flowing clear water in canals, rivulets, rivers etc. After several days of immersion, the jute fibre gets loosen from the stalk and is extracted from the jute stalk which becomes the byproduct.;This dataset serves as the transformation process of jute plant to fibre. ;[This dataset was recalculated on 20230912, since the BD dataset was corrected on the same period.]

The activity starts with the immersion of the jute plant bundles into the water.

The activity ends with the extraction of the jute fibres from the retted plants. In Bangladesh, Single Stem Stripping is mostly used to extract fibres. It is done manually by hand. The Jute Fibre is then gets dried in the sun.
category: C:Manufacturing/13:Manufacture of textiles/131:Spinning, weaving and finishing of textiles/1311:Preparation and spinning of textile fibres

processDocumentation.geographyDescription: This dataset is a weighted average built from the following geographies: BD, IN.
processDocumentation.technologyDescription: The retting activity is usually accomplished either on the jute growing field or in canals, by immersion of the bundles of jute into stagnant water.
processDocumentation.dataTreatmentDescription: This dataset is a weighted average between primary data from India and Bangladesh, based on their production volumes. Uncertainty was adjusted accordingly.
processDocumentation.samplingDescription:
This dataset was built as a weighted average of regional datasets of the same activityName. Weights are based on production volumes.
BD: production volume = 1.60e+09 kg/year, weight = 0.4835
IN: production volume = 1.71e+09 kg/year, weight = 0.5165

exchanges.description: This exchange is a weighted average of the BD (48.35%) and IN (51.65%) datasets with same activity name (fibre production, jute, retting). For more details, please consult the regional activity.

exchanges.description:
The output of the jute cultivation activity. This exchange is a weighted average of the BD (48.35%) and IN (51.65%) datasets with same activity name (fibre production, jute, retting). For more details, please consult the regional activity.
Mature jute plant is harvested. Jute is generally harvested when the plants are at early pod stage. The harvest index remains more or less constant over 60-105 day period following sowing. However, it reaches its peak during 110-120 day period following sowing. 
The plants are usually cut close to the ground by hand. A curved, sickle type knife is used to cut the plants. The plants are then sorted out according to height and diameter. The assorted plants are tied into bundles. Each bundle weighs 8-10 kg. The bundles are kept standing in the field for 3-4 days for defoliation.
